Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members of the board of the US Federal Reserve gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future course.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to miss its most important mandate – ensuring price stability – to such an extent.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional soul-searching is certainly appropriate.
Yet while monetary policy is making headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
Another big question therefore is whether it will use its huge power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could refuse to grant credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant credit only to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit towards desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to explicitly take on regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by prescribing to banks where and to whom credit should be granted, who should be hired and who should be fired, and so on.
However, before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move in, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the US government made a consequential decision: Financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments by selling short-term, run-vulnerable debt instruments, but hordes of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk vulnerability of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgage loans in bank balance sheets.
Yet in the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred at the beginning of 2020, the Fed discarded its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even greater scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for ordinary US government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed again rescued the money market funds.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the rescue package for the financial sector - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
But in 2020, they had introduced an explicit lower bound for corporate bond prices, among other things, with the "Powell put".
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We need not worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the US Treasury will simply extinguish any new blaze with another wave of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother to go to the trouble of using liquidity provisions or balance sheet space for purchases at falling prices, or treating a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will inevitably outfly them all and pocket the profits.
Why would companies still issue shares when they could simply take out a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why do investors hesitate when it comes to buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed in tough times?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will cover the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, state pensions and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
But each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to invest even more money in rescue operations and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages from everyone do not materialize, we will wake up to a big fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulatory authorities and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, people indulged themselves only in self-satisfaction regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of the subprime mortgages just as little as it did the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about the aforementioned events.
And although alphabet soups about "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" are produced, they have not succeeded in defining the "systemic" risk at all, aside from the fact that it has become a catch-all term that grants the regulatory authorities comprehensive power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions or ensure that immense debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always steps in to cover mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
Enormous compliance costs constitute a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory rules are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of undesired consequences or well designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not yet another thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital offers a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have clairvoyant abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before she commits herself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
